firewalld is a firewall management tool used in many Linux distributions, particularly Red Hat-based systems like:
RHEL (Red Hat Enterprise Linux)
CentOS
Fedora
Rocky Linux
AlmaLinux

It provides a dynamic way to manage firewall rules without restarting the firewall service, and it supports zones, services, and rich rules for granular control.

ðŸ”¥ What Firewalld Does:

Controls access to network services. 
Blocks or allows traffic based on rules.
Uses zones to define trust levels for network connections.
Can be configured permanent or runtime (temporary).

[+] Installation:
# sudo apt install firewalld 
# sudo firewall-cmd --state 

# sudo firewall-cmd --permanent --add-port=80/tcp
# sudo firewall-cmd --permanent --add-port=443/tcp

# sudo firewall-cmd --reload
# sudo firewall-cmd --list-services

# sudo firewall-cmd --permanent --add-port=53/udp
# sudo firewalld -h

# sudo firewalld --permanent --add-port=80/tcp
# sudo firewalld-cmd --list-services

# sudo firewalld-cmd --zone=public --add-rich-rule='rule family ="ipv4" source address="IP" drop'
# sudo firewall-cmd --set-zone=home
